{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533147"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:33:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:33:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14759"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14759"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.8,0.06,0.07,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58448"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7450"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43864"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"3005"},{"type":"tags","id":"3645"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"6488"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11701"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18229"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44421"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58448"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of intermittent painless haematuria and increased urinary frequency. He immigrated from Egypt eight years ago and last visited three months ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 124/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft and non-tender with no organomegaly. Digital rectal examination reveals no masses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin 128 g/L (130-170)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count 9.2 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEosinophils 1.8 x 10^9/L (0.0-0.4)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets 245 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine microscopy shows red blood cells and parasitic eggs. CT urogram reveals irregular bladder wall thickening with calcification.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trichomonas vaginalis","Schistosoma haematobium","Echinococcus granulosus","Strongyloides stercoralis","Enterobius vermicularis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of chronic urogenital schistosomiasis complicated by bladder cancer, as suggested by the haematuria, bladder wall thickening, and calcification on imaging. \u003Cstrong\u003ESchistosoma haematobium\u003C/strong\u003E is the causative organism, being the only schistosome species that primarily affects the urogenital system. The presence of eosinophilia and exposure history in Egypt, where \u003Cem\u003ES. haematobium\u003C/em\u003E is endemic, supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrichomonas vaginalis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause urethritis and dysuria but does not cause chronic bladder wall changes or cancer. While it can cause urinary symptoms, it would not explain the eosinophilia or bladder calcification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEchinococcus granulosus\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes hydatid cysts in the liver and lungs. While it can rarely affect the urinary tract, it would present as cystic lesions rather than diffuse bladder wall changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStrongyloides stercoralis\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the gastrointestinal tract and can cause eosinophilia, but it does not typically involve the urinary tract. Its lifecycle involves skin penetration and pulmonary migration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnterobius vermicularis\u003C/strong\u003E (pinworm) causes perianal irritation and nocturnal pruritis. While it can occasionally enter the genitourinary tract in females, it does not cause chronic bladder inflammation or cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to diagnosis is recognising the combination of haematuria, bladder wall changes, eosinophilia, and appropriate geographical exposure. \u003Cem\u003ES. haematobium\u003C/em\u003E infection leads to chronic inflammation and fibrosis of the bladder wall, significantly increasing the risk of squamous cell carcinoma of the bladder.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic Schistosoma haematobium infection is a major risk factor for bladder cancer in endemic regions.","Haematuria and lower urinary tract symptoms are typical presenting features of urogenital schistosomiasis.","Travel history and exposure to freshwater in endemic areas are crucial diagnostic clues for schistosomiasis."],"references":["McManus DP, Dunne DW, Sacko M, Utzinger J, Vennervald BJ, Zhou XN. Schistosomiasis. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2018;4(1):13. Published 2018 Aug 9. doi:10.1038/s41572-018-0013-8","Lo NC, Bezerra FSM, Colley DG, et al. Review of 2022 WHO guidelines on the control and elimination of schistosomiasis. Lancet Infect Dis. 2022;22(11):e327-e335. doi:10.1016/S1473-3099(22)00221-3"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43864"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14759"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43864"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-31T18:32:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T18:35:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7450"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58448"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description